      <comment>Undid revision 430984179 by [[Special:Contributions/114.198.42.255|114.198.42.255]] ([[User talk:114.198.42.255|talk]])revert change . . . timeline includes [[Book of Ether]]</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Other uses|Book of Mormon (disambiguation)}}
{{for|the Broadway musical|The Book of Mormon (musical)}}
{{Book of Mormon}}
The '''Book of Mormon''' is a [[sacred text]] of the [[Latter Day Saint movement]].  It was first published in March 1830 by [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]] as ''The Book of Mormon: An Account Written by the Hand of Mormon upon Plates Taken from the Plates of Nephi''.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvtxt|Smith|1830|loc=title page}}. In 1982, in an effort to clarify and emphasize its purpose, [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) retitled its editions of the book to ''The Book of Mormon: Another Testament of Jesus Christ'' {{harvtxt|LDS Church|2008}}.&lt;/ref&gt; According to Smith's account, and also according to the book's narrative, the Book of Mormon was originally written in otherwise unknown characters referred to as &quot;[[reformed Egyptian]]&quot; &lt;ref&gt;([http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/morm/9.32?lang=eng#31 Mormon 9:32 -- LDS edition])&lt;/ref&gt; engraved on [[golden plates]]. Smith said that he received these plates in 1827 from an [[Angel Moroni|angel named Moroni]],&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvtxt|Roberts|1902|pp=11, 18–19}}.&lt;/ref&gt; whom Smith identified as a [[resurrection#Mormonism|resurrected]]&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvtxt|Smith|1838|pp=42–43}}.&lt;/ref&gt; [[indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous American]] who had written and abridged parts of the book over a millennium prior to the encounter. According to Smith, [[Moroni (Book of Mormon)|Moroni]] had buried the plates in a stone box, along with other ancient artifacts,&lt;ref&gt;See also [[Sword of Laban]], [[Urim and Thummim (Latter Day Saints)|Urim and Thummim]]&lt;/ref&gt; in a hill near Smith's home in [[Manchester (town), New York|Manchester]], [[New York]].

The Book of Mormon is the earliest of the defining publications of the Latter Day Saint movement.  The churches of the movement typically regard the Book of Mormon not only as scripture, but as a historical record of God's dealings with the ancient inhabitants of the [[Americas]],&lt;ref&gt;[http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/introduction?lang=eng &quot;Introduction&quot;], Book of Mormon (1981 LDS Church ed.).&lt;/ref&gt; written by American [[prophet]]s&lt;ref&gt;[[Gordon B. Hinckley]], [http://speeches.byu.edu/reader/reader.php?id=6730 &quot;Praise to the Man&quot;], 1979-11-04.&lt;/ref&gt; from perhaps as early as 2600 BC to about AD 421.&lt;ref&gt;[[Church Educational System]] (1996, rev. ed.). [http://www.ldsces.org/inst_manuals/bm-in-sm1996/manualindex.asp ''Book of Mormon Student Manual''] (Salt Lake City, Utah: The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints), ch. 6.&lt;/ref&gt;

The Book of Mormon is divided into smaller books, titled after the individuals named as primary authors and, in most versions, divided into chapters and verses.  It is written in English, very similar to the [[Early Modern English]] linguistic style of the [[King James Version]] of the Bible, and has since been fully or partially translated into 108 languages.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.fairlds.org/FAIR_Brochures/King_James_Bible_and_the_Book_of_Mormon.pdf&lt;/ref&gt;  The Book of Mormon has a number of original and distinctive doctrinal discussions on subjects such as the fall of [[Adam and Eve (LDS Church)|Adam and Eve]],&lt;ref&gt;See for [http://scriptures.lds.org/en/2_ne/2 example]&lt;/ref&gt; the nature of the [[Atonement in Christianity|Atonement]],&lt;ref&gt;See for [http://scriptures.lds.org/en/2_ne/9 example]&lt;/ref&gt; [[eschatology]], redemption from physical and spiritual death,&lt;ref&gt;See for [http://scriptures.lds.org/en/alma/12 example]&lt;/ref&gt; and the organization of the [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|latter-day church]].

==Origin==
{{Main|Origin of the Book of Mormon|Golden plates|Criticism of the Book of Mormon}}

[[File:Basic BOM Manuscripts.jpg|thumb|A page from the original manuscript of the Book of Mormon, covering {{lds|1 Nephi|1_ne|4|38}}{{lds|-|1_ne|5|14}}]]
Joseph Smith Jr. said that when he was seventeen &lt;!-- do not edit age, JS was 17 at time of Moroni visit, see refs for clarification --&gt;years of age an angel of God, named [[Moroni (prophet)|Moroni]], appeared to him,&lt;ref name=&quot;lds.org&quot;&gt;“The Life and Ministry of Joseph Smith,” Teachings of Presidents of the Church: Joseph Smith, (2007),xxii–25 [http://www.lds.org/ldsorg/v/index.jsp?vgnextoid=da135f74db46c010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&amp;locale=0&amp;sourceId=724720596a845110VgnVCM100000176f620a____&amp;hideNav=1&amp;contentLocale=0]&lt;/ref&gt; and said that a collection of ancient writings, engraved on [[golden plates]] by ancient prophets, was buried in a [[Cumorah|nearby hill]] in [[Wayne County, New York]]. The writings described a people whom God had led from Jerusalem to the Western Hemisphere 600 years before Jesus’ birth. According to the narrative, Moroni was the last prophet among these people and had buried the record, which God had promised to bring forth in the latter days.  Smith stated that he was instructed by Moroni to meet at the hill annually each September 22 to receive further instructions and that four years after the initial visit, in 1827, he was allowed to take the plates and was directed to translate them into English.&lt;ref name=&quot;lds.org&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://scriptures.lds.org/en/js_h/1/59#59 ''Pearl Of Great Price,'' Joseph SMith - History 1:59]&lt;/ref&gt;

Smith's first published description of the plates said the plates &quot;had the appearance of gold,&quot; and were described by [[Martin Harris (Latter Day Saints)|Martin Harris]], one of Smith's early scribes, to be &quot;fastened together in the shape of a book by wires.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal
 | last=Smith
 | first=Joseph, Jr.
 | author-link=Joseph Smith, Jr.
 | title=Church History [Wentworth Letter]
 | place=[[Nauvoo, Illinois]]
 | journal=[[Times and Seasons]]
 | date=March 1, 1842
 | volume=3
 | issue=9
 | pages=906–936
 | url=http://www.centerplace.org/history/ts/v3n09.htm
 | ref=harv
 }}.&lt;/ref&gt; Smith called the engraved writing on the plates &quot;[[reformed Egyptian]]&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;Only LDS linguists accept the existence of any language or character set known as &quot;reformed Egyptian&quot; as described in LDS tradition.  The only example of reformed Egyptian extant is the &quot;Caractors Document&quot;, also known as the &quot;Anthon Transcript&quot;, a paper written by Smith with examples of what he claimed to be &quot;reformed Egyptian&quot; characters.  See [[Reformed Egyptian]] for details and references.&lt;/ref&gt; A portion of the text on the plates was also &quot;[[Golden_plates#.22Sealed.22_portion|sealed]]&quot; according to his account, so its content was not included in the Book of Mormon.&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvtxt|Smith|1842|p=707}}.&lt;/ref&gt;

In addition to Smith's account regarding the plates, eleven others signed [[affidavits]] that they saw and handled the golden plates for themselves. Their written testimonies are known as the Testimony of [[Three Witnesses]]&lt;ref&gt;[http://scriptures.lds.org/bm/thrwtnss Testimony of Three Witnesses]&lt;/ref&gt; and the Testimony of [[Eight Witnesses]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://scriptures.lds.org/bm/eghtwtns Testimony of Eight Witnesses]&lt;/ref&gt; These affidavits are published as part of the introductory pages to the Book of Mormon.

Smith enlisted the help of his neighbor, Martin Harris (one of the Three Witnesses), who later mortgaged his farm to underwrite the printing of the Book of Mormon, as a scribe during his initial work on the text. In 1828, Harris, prompted by his wife, [[Lucy Harris]], repeatedly requested that Smith lend him the current pages that had been translated. Smith reluctantly relented to Harris' requests. Lucy Harris is thought to have stolen the [[Lost 116 pages|first 116 pages]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Lucy Harris&quot;&gt;{{Harvnb|Hitchens|2007|pp=163}}, {{Harvnb|Givens|2002|pp=33}}, {{Harvnb|Givens|2002|pp=33}}&lt;/ref&gt; After the loss, Smith recorded that he had lost the ability to translate, and that Moroni had taken back the plates to be returned only after Smith repented.&lt;ref&gt;''[[Doctrine and Covenants]]'', [[s:The Doctrine and Covenants/Section 3|Section 3]] and&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;autogenerated2&quot;&gt;{{Harvnb|Brodie|1971}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvnb|Givens|2002}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvnb|Hitchens|2007|pp=163–164}}&lt;/ref&gt; Smith later stated that God allowed him to resume translation, but directed that he begin translating another part of the plates.  In 1829, with the assistance of [[Oliver Cowdery]], work on the Book of Mormon recommenced, and was completed in a remarkably short period (April–June 1829).&lt;ref&gt;[[Joseph Smith: Rough Stone Rolling]] (New York: Alfred A. Knopf, 2005), 70.&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;  Smith said that he then returned the plates to Moroni upon the publication of the book.&lt;ref name=&quot;autogenerated2&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://scriptures.lds.org/en/bm/jstestimony Testimony of Joseph Smith] {{Harvnb|Hitchens|2007|pp=164}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Book of Mormon went on sale at the bookstore of E. B. Grandin on March 26, 1830.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal
|last=Kunz
|first=Ryan
|date=March 2010
|title=180 Years Later, Book of Mormon Nears 150 Million Copies
|journal=[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]
|publisher=Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints
|pages=74–76
|url=http://lds.org/ensign/2010/03/180-years-later-book-of-mormon-nears-150-million-copies?lang=eng
|accessdate=2011-03-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; Today the building in which the Book of Mormon was first published and sold is known as the [[Book of Mormon Historic Publication Site]].

Critics of the Book of Mormon claim the book was fabricated by Smith&lt;ref name=&quot;Tanner Shadow&quot;&gt;{{cite book|
title=Mormonism - Shadow or Reality?|
isbn=9993074438|
