==Phrygian or Amorian dynasty (820–867)==

{{See also|Byzantium under the Amorian dynasty}}

{|width=100% class=&quot;wikitable&quot;
! colspan=&quot;2&quot; style=&quot;width:25%;&quot;|Name
!style=&quot;width:15%;&quot;|Reign
!Comments
|-
|align=center|[[File:Michael II and Theophilos solidus.jpg|80px]]||align=center|[[Michael II|Michael II &quot;the Stammerer&quot; or &quot;the Amorian&quot;]]&lt;br&gt;(Μιχαήλ Β΄ ο Τραυλός/Ψελλός, ο εξ Αμορίου)||align=&quot;center&quot;|25 December 820 –&lt;br/&gt;2 October 829||align=&quot;left&quot;|Born in 770 at [[Amorium]], he became an army officer. A friend of Leo V, he was raised to high office but led the conspiracy that murdered him. Survived the rebellion of [[Thomas the Slav]], lost [[Crete]] to the Arabs and faced the beginning of the [[Muslim conquest of Sicily]], reinforced iconoclasm
|-
|align=center|[[Image:Emperor Theophilos Chronicle of John Skylitzes.jpg|80px]]||align=center|[[Theophilos (emperor)|Theophilos]]&lt;br&gt;(Θεόφιλος)||align=&quot;center&quot;|2 October 829 –&lt;br/&gt;20 January 842||align=&quot;left&quot;|Born in 813, as the only son of Michael II. Co-emperor since 821, he succeeded on his father's death.
|-
|align=center|[[File:Michael iii.jpg|80px]]||align=center|[[Michael III|Michael III &quot;the Drunkard&quot;]]&lt;br&gt;(Μιχαήλ Γ΄ ο Μέθυσος)&lt;br&gt;||align=&quot;center&quot;|20 January 842 –&lt;br/&gt;23 September 867||align=&quot;left&quot;|Born on 19 January 840, he succeeded on Theophilos' death. Under the regency of his mother [[Theodora the Armenian|Theodora]] until 856, and of his uncle [[Bardas]] in 862–866. Ended iconoclasm. Murdered by Basil the Macedonian. A pleasure-loving ruler, he was nicknamed &quot;the Drunkard&quot; by later, pro-Basil chroniclers 
|-
|}

